body:
The thing that confuses me is the benchmark they use. 
For some reason, they look at "people killed by police". See that blacks are killed by police 26-27% of the time, and THEN compare that to ... the population numbers? 

This is obviously just a stupid thing to do, since you would actually want to use a proper benchmark. The question of which numbers we should look at when deriving how often we’d expect black people to be killed by police absent of any bias is best answered by looking at the actual relevant data. 
Like people shooting at police, violent crime, percent of the murderers, etc. Something like that. 
But you don't fucking use "population numbers". This is just so obviously stupid, I am not even sure why one would even have to explain this.
